Merge pull request #107 from JeffBNimble/filter-logic

Tweak the filter logic when applying filters

Tweak the filter logic when applying filters

Previously, the filter logic grouped the filters into categories;
Level, Path, Function and Message. Within each category, all
required filters had to pass and at least one non-required filter
had to pass. Then, each category was ANDed together to make
sure all filters passed according to these rules.

This change slightly alters the logic and the results are nearly identical. However,
it is likely easier to understand. Now, all required filters are gathered regardless of
category and all must pass. Then, all non-required filters are gathered and at least
one of them must pass and then both groups must pass.

Merge pull request #106 from JeffBNimble/destination-filtering

Add new filtering implementation and deprecated minLevelFilters

Add new filtering implementation and deprecated minLevelFilters

There are now multiple individual and flexible filters that can be
added/removed to a destination to better control what gets logged
to the destination. You can add any combination of Path, Function and/or
Message filters using a flexible comparison mechanism. Logged messages
can use startsWith, contains, endsWith or equals filters and each can
be case sensitive or not.

Add content filtering

This PR allows Content Filters to be added to a destination to further
control what gets sent to the destination. A ContentFilter, when applied, answers
true or false. Answering true allows the message to be logged. If multiple content
filters have been added to a destination, ANY filter answering true will allow the message
to be logged even if others answer false.

Merge pull request #98 from JeffBNimble/enhancements

Move message resolution to background

Move message resolution to background

Though most of the time, message resolution will likely not be expensive, this
change moves the resolution of the message to the asynchronous dispatch queue.

In order to accommodate this change, I had to change all @autoclosure annotations to
@autoclosure(escaping). According to the article posted here:
http://ericasadun.com/2015/04/30/swift-a-little-autoclosure-hacking/, non escaping @autoclosures
provide minor performance optimizations.

Merge pull request #92 from ewanmellor/allow-blank-messages

Allow empty log messages.

Allow empty log messages.

These were deliberately being thrown away, but for no apparent reason.

The log message will eventually contain useful information, like the
source location, time, and thread, and so there's value in having a log
message emitted even if the "message" is empty.

This means that client code can do log.debug("") and still see when that
line is reached, or log.error("\(serverError)") and still see that
something bad happened, even if the server returned nothing.
